<HL>
   Business Brief -- Maxtor Corp.:
   Offer of $40 Million Made
   For Assets of MiniScribe
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MXTR MINQE
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   Maxtor Corp. said it made a $40 million offer to buy
substantially all of the assets of MiniScribe Corp., a
troubled Longmont, Colo., maker of computer disk drives.
   Maxtor, a maker of data-storage products, said the offer
consists of $20 million in cash, and $20 million in stock. In
addition, Maxtor, based in San Jose, Calif., will lend
MiniScribe as much as $30 million for working capital between
acceptance of the offer and the closing date.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   MiniScribe has been operating under Chapter 11 of the
federal Bankruptcy Code since Jan. 1. Its assets are
scheduled to be offered for sale in U.S. bankruptcy court
tomorrow.
   In Longmont, MiniScribe couldn't be reached for comment.
It wasn't clear whether the company has received other bids.
</TEXT>
